The general expression for thermodynamic boundary work is $W = -integral_1^2 P d V$. 
  For an isothermal process of an ideal gas, substituting $P = (n R T) / V$ yields:
  $ W = -integral_1^2 (n R T) / V d V = -n R T ln(V_2 / V_1) = -n R T ln(P_1 / P_2) $
  
  Substituting the given parameters ($n = 10 " mol"$, $T = 300 " K"$, $P_1 = 1 " atm"$, $P_2 = 10 " atm"$):
  $ W = -10 " mol" times 8.314 " J mol"^(-1) "K"^(-1) times 300 " K" times ln(1 / 10) approx +57.4 " kJ" $
  
  Since the gas is compressed, work is performed *on* the gas ($W > 0$). In the reverse expansion process, the gas does work on the surroundings, meaning the work done *on* the gas is equal in magnitude but opposite in sign ($W = -57.4 " kJ"$).